title: Compensation when a road affects your property's value

heading_context: Compensation when a road affects your property's value
When you can claim
chunks.html_content:
You can apply for compensation if the value of your property goes down because of pollution or disturbance from the use of a new or altered road.

This is known as a ‘Part I claim’.

You can claim after a road’s been open to traffic for 1 year.

How to claim
chunks.html_content:
1. Check you have a valid claim.

  2. Check where to send your claim.

You can make a claim yourself or use an agent (eg a professional property valuer or claims company) to claim for you.

heading_context: Compensation when a road affects your property's value
What you can claim for
chunks.html_content:
The value of your property must have gone down by more than £50 as the result of specific types of pollution or disturbance from the use of a new or altered road.

You can only make a Part I claim because of:

  • noise
  • vibration
  • smell
  • fumes
  • smoke
  • artificial lighting
  • solid or liquid discharge on to your property
chunks.plain_content:

What you can claim for
The value of your property must have gone down by more than £50 as the result of specific types of pollution or disturbance from the use of a new or altered road.
You can only make a Part I claim because of:

  noise
  vibration
  smell
  fumes
  smoke
  artificial lighting
  solid or liquid discharge on to your property

heading_context: Compensation when a road affects your property's value
What you can’t claim for
chunks.html_content:
You can’t make a Part I claim for:

  • other problems caused by a road, eg losing your view, natural light or privacy (sometimes called ‘blight’)
  • problems coming from another part of the road - your claim must be for the part of the road that’s new or altered
  • a road that’s only been resurfaced

heading_context: Compensation when a road affects your property's value
Types of property you can claim for
Homes
chunks.html_content:
You can usually only claim for property you own and occupy.

You must own the property both:

  • before the road opened to traffic
  • when you make your claim

You must also be able to prove you own 1 of the following:

  • the property’s freehold
  • the property’s leasehold, with at least 3 years left to run on your lease on the date you make your claim

You can’t claim for property that was part of a ‘compulsory purchase’ for the construction of the road.

You must be living in the property when you make your claim, unless you can’t because:

  • you let it to tenants
  • there’s another legal reason preventing you, eg a court order

heading_context: Compensation when a road affects your property's value
Types of property you can claim for
Business premises
chunks.html_content:
You must occupy the whole property, or a substantial part of it, both:

  • before the road opened to traffic
  • when you make your claim

Your property’s rateable value must be below £34,800.

heading_context: Compensation when a road affects your property's value
Make a claim to Highways England
chunks.html_content:
You usually need to make your claim to the authority responsible for the road - this is:

  • your local council for local roads
  • Highways England for major roads, including motorways and some A roads

You need to make your claim to Connect Plus if it’s for M25 widening at:

  • junctions 16 to 23
  • junctions 27 to 30

  1. Check Part I claims notices for roads that are open for claims.

  2. Read the guide to Part I claims.

  3. Download and fill in the claim for compensation form.

  4. Send your claim to the Highways England.
